<leg:level id="UCPN.OL.VPAN08.S7"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="sect" searchtype="LEGISLATION SECT" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[440,030] s 7 Inherent jurisdiction and powers of courts and tribunals not limited">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.OL.VPAN08.S7" type="ext"/>[440,030]</edpnum><title searchtype="SECT-TITLE">Inherent jurisdiction and powers of courts and tribunals not limited</title><desig searchtype="SECT-NUM"><designum>7</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>This Act does not limit or otherwise affect any inherent jurisdiction or any powers that a court or tribunal has apart from this Act to restrict vexatious proceedings.</text></p>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.OL.VPAN08.S7.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_OL.SGM_UCPN.OL.440030-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[440,030.5] Inherent and implied jurisdiction">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [440,030.5] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text>Â </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_ACT_1970-52" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Supreme Court Act 1970</remotelink> SCA s 84.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_REG_2005-418" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Uniform Civil Procedure Rules 2005</remotelink> r 14.28.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.OL.440030-5" type="ext"/>[440,030.5] </edpnum><title>Inherent and implied jurisdiction</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The Act specifically does not limit the inherent jurisdiction of the court. Doubts had previously been expressed in relation to 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.SC.SCA70.S84" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">SCA s 84</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 about the extent to which the inherent jurisdiction permits orders restraining a party from commencing proceedings or from lodging appeals: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1974"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000551" spanref="cr000551-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="131"/><ci:page num="311"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000551" spanref="cr000551-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="320" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000552" spanref="cr000552-003"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:page num="19"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000553" spanref="cr000553-004"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC7400019"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Commonwealth Trading Bank of Australia v Inglis</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000551-001" status="unval">(1974) 131 CLR 311</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000551-002" status="unval">at 320</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000552-003">3 ALR 19</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000553-004"> BC7400019</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="14689" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1992"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000554" spanref="cr000554-001"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="109"/><ci:page num="303"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000555" spanref="cr000555-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALJR"/><ci:volume num="66"/><ci:page num="810"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000556" spanref="cr000556-003"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9202692"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Jones v Skyring</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000554-001">(1992) 109 ALR 303</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000555-002" status="unval">66 ALJR 810</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000556-003"> BC9202692</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="36595" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>, except in those cases where the restraint was limited to preventing conduct involving relitigation of matters that had already been decided: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1999"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000557" spanref="cr000557-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="FCR"/><ci:volume num="91"/><ci:page num="214"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000558" spanref="cr000558-002"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9904501"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Hunter v Leahy</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000557-001" status="unval">(1999) 91 FCR 214</ci:span>; [1999] FCA 1075; <ci:span spanid="cr000558-002"> BC9904501</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="300748" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (French J).</text></p>
<p>
<text>The court has an inherent jurisdiction to prevent abuse of its process, as well as a rule based power to stay or dismiss proceedings: see UCPR 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R14-28" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">r 14.28</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
. In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000559" spanref="cr000559-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="Ch"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="2000"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="484"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000559" spanref="cr000559-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="496" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000560" spanref="cr000560-003" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WLR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1999"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="670"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Ebert v Venvil</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000559-001" status="unval">[2000] Ch 484</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000559-002" status="unval">at 496&#x2013;7</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000560-003" status="unval">[1999] 3 WLR 670</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="301859" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>, after an extensive review, the English Court of Appeal held that the inherent power did permit orders restraining a vexatious litigant from bringing new proceedings that would constitute an abuse of process. That power was even held to extend to restraining the commencement of proceedings in the subordinate courts. Furthermore, the inherent jurisdiction has been held to permit orders preventing a party from making frivolous or unnecessary interlocutory applications in pending proceedings: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1887"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000561" spanref="cr000561-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ChD"/><ci:volume num="37"/><ci:page num="168"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Grepe v Loam</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000561-001" status="unval">(1887) 37 Ch D 168</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="39069" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000562" spanref="cr000562-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="Ch"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1905"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="306"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Lord Kinnaird v Field</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000562-001" status="unval">[1905] 2 Ch 306</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="279543" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1930"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000563" spanref="cr000563-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNNSW"/><ci:volume num="47"/><ci:page num="19"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Davison v Colonial Treasurer</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000563-001" status="unval">(1930) 47 WN (NSW) 19</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="132462" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1974"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000564" spanref="cr000564-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="131"/><ci:page num="311"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000564" spanref="cr000564-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="320" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000565" spanref="cr000565-003"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:page num="19"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000565" spanref="cr000565-004"><ci:pinpoint num="26" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000566" spanref="cr000566-005"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC7400019"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Commonwealth Trading Bank of Australia v Inglis</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000564-001" status="unval">(1974) 131 CLR 311</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000564-002" status="unval">at 320</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000565-003">3 ALR 19</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000565-004">at 26</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000566-005"> BC7400019</ci:span></citefragment>Â <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="14689" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Hillston v Bar-Mordechai</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2002] NSWSC 975:BC200207617</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
